The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Saturday, April 17, 2004 				 Pak tribe to hunt for militants
																								Wana, April 16 (Reuters): A Pakistani tribe whose members are accused of harbouring al Qaida fighters is preparing to launch a hunt for the militants, after those sheltering them refused to surrender, tribal elders said today.																								The decision came after five men said to be sheltering al Qaida rebels near the Afghan border rejected demands by a traditional tribal assembly either to surrender, leave the area or promise not to protect foreign militants. Tribal elder Malik Shireen Jan said the hunt by a force of tribesmen numbering nearly 2,000 men for al Qaida militants and their Pakistani allies would be launched tomorrow.																								We will not spare these people because they are bent upon destroying our area, he told tribal representatives in the western town of Wana, 380 km southwest of Islamabad.																								President Pervez Musharraf, a key ally in the US-led war on terror, has vowed to clear foreign militants from the lawless tribal areas on the Afghan border.																								He blamed militants with links to tribal areas for attacks across Pakistan, including two attempts on his life in December.																								About 5,000 Pakistan troops launched a major operation last month near Wana to flush out members of al Qaida, Afghanistans ousted Taliban militia and Pakistani tribesman sheltering them. Afghan troops																								The US, which has increased troops numbers in Afghanistan to hunt for Osama bin Laden and other militants, may cut them back after the country holds elections, the top US military officer said today.																								General Richard Myers said his forces in Afghanistan were moving to uproot al Qaida militants and their Taliban allies.
